<title>The dot product</title>

<definition><statement><p>For
    two-dimensional vectors <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\wvec</m>, their dot
    product <m>\vvec\cdot\wvec</m> is the scalar defined to be
    <me>
      \vvec\cdot\wvec = \twovec{v_1}{v_2}\cdot\twovec{w_1}{w_2} =
      v_1w_1 + v_2w_2\text{.}
    </me></p></statement></definition>

    <definition><statement>
      <idx> dot product </idx>
      <p>For
    <m>n</m>-dimensional vectors <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\wvec</m>, their dot
    product <m>\vvec\cdot\wvec</m> is the scalar defined to be
    <me>
      \vvec\cdot\wvec  =
      v_1w_1 + v_2w_2+\cdots + v_nw_n\text{.}
    </me></p></statement></definition>


<activity>
      <introduction>
      <p>  Suppose that <m>\vvec=\twovec{3}{4}</m> and <m>\wvec=\twovec{2}{-2}</m>.</p></introduction>
     
    
    <task><p>Compute the dot product
    <m>\vvec\cdot\wvec
    </m>.</p></task>
    <task><p> Sketch the vector <m>\vvec</m>.  Then
    use the Pythagorean theorem to find the length of <m>\vvec</m>. </p></task>
    <task><p>Compute the dot product <m>\vvec\cdot\vvec</m>.  How
    is the dot product related to the length of <m>\vvec</m>? </p></task>
    

    </activity>

    <definition>
      <statement>
  <idx> magnitude of a vector </idx>
  
  <p> The <term>magnitude</term>, or length, of <m>\vvec</m>, which we denote as
      <m>\len{\vvec}</m>, is <m>\len{\vvec} = \sqrt{(v_1)^2 + (v_2)^2+\cdots +
      (v_n)^2}</m>.
  </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>We saw in the first activity that <m>\vvec\cdot\vvec = \len{\vvec}^2</m>.</p>

    <definition><statement><idx>orthogonal</idx>
    <p>Two vectors <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\wvec</m> are perpendicular or <term>orthogonal</term> if <m>\vvec\cdot\wvec=0</m>.</p></statement></definition>

<activity>
